This command:

eas build --platform android

uses Expo Application Services to create an Android app build in the cloud.

🧠 Simple meaning

Instead of building APK/AAB on your laptop:

Gradle + Android Studio + local build

Expo uploads your project to Expo servers and builds it there.

✅ What it generates

Depending on profile:

Command	Output
eas build --platform android --profile preview	APK
eas build --platform android --profile production	AAB
📦 APK vs AAB
Type	Use
APK	Direct install/testing
AAB	Google Play Store upload
🚀 What happens internally

When you run:

eas build --platform android

Expo does:

Reads your:
app.json
eas.json
Uploads source code to Expo cloud
Installs dependencies
Runs Android Gradle build
Signs app
Generates:
.apk
OR
.aab
Gives download URL
📍 Example

Your eas.json has:

"preview": {
  "distribution": "internal",
  "android": {
    "buildType": "apk"
  }
}

So this command:

eas build --platform android --profile preview

👉 creates APK.

🏪 Production build
eas build --platform android --profile production

👉 creates Play Store AAB.

☁️ Why EAS is useful

Benefits:

✅ No Android Studio needed for release builds
✅ No local Gradle headaches
✅ Easier signing
✅ CI/CD friendly
✅ Team collaboration
✅ Safer keystore management

⚠️ Important

You must:

eas login

before build.

And project must have valid:

"projectId"

inside app.json.

💡 Your common commands
APK
eas build --platform android --profile preview
AAB
eas build --platform android --profile production
TestFlight
eas build --platform ios --profile production
